00:02:41.420 --> 00:02:43.440
your newly minted
jobs, as docents.

00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:44.840
So here's the thing.

00:02:44.840 --> 00:02:48.390
The main points of
my presentation are

00:02:48.390 --> 00:02:53.180
that the Library of Congress
that Benjamin Latrobe,

00:02:53.180 --> 00:02:55.630
as you all know, who was the
first architect of the Capitol,

00:02:55.630 --> 00:02:59.330
started a century-long
process with Thomas Jefferson.

00:02:59.330 --> 00:03:02.850
They started architectural
and iconographic traditions

00:03:02.850 --> 00:03:05.810
which continued through
the innovative designs

00:03:05.810 --> 00:03:09.860
of Charles Bulfinch and Thomas
Walter, eventually resulting

00:03:09.860 --> 00:03:12.890
in our magnificent Thomas
Jefferson Building today.

00:03:12.890 --> 00:03:16.410
These traditions include
homage and tribute

00:03:16.410 --> 00:03:19.670
to ancient cultures'
advancements in, and methods of,

00:03:19.670 --> 00:03:21.260
the transmission of learning.

00:03:21.260 --> 00:03:25.060
Okay? The Library became
a symbol of patriotism

00:03:25.060 --> 00:03:27.020
and accomplishment early.

00:03:27.020 --> 00:03:28.490
And I'm talking 1808.

00:03:28.490 --> 00:03:32.390
And we are going to look at
that in detail in just a moment.

00:03:32.390 --> 00:03:35.680
Careful attention to storing
and preserving printed materials

00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:40.100
in beautiful and majestic, as
well as very functional spaces.

00:03:40.100 --> 00:03:43.970
Okay? The adaptation of
neo-classical design conventions

00:03:43.970 --> 00:03:46.010
to American themes
and landscape,

00:03:46.010 --> 00:03:49.750
including the introduction
of Roman gods and goddesses

00:03:49.750 --> 00:03:51.830
to celebrate American
achievement,

00:03:51.830 --> 00:03:54.210
and the use of the
allegorical female

00:03:54.210 --> 00:03:56.870
to represent noble
human attributes.

00:03:56.870 --> 00:04:00.180
The use of innovative and
cutting edge technology not only

00:04:00.180 --> 00:04:03.350
to preserve the collections
and safeguard them from fire,

00:04:03.350 --> 00:04:06.150
in particular, but
also to make the space

00:04:06.150 --> 00:04:08.850
as noteworthy architectural
achievements.

00:04:08.850 --> 00:04:12.630
And also to provide as much
natural light as possible.

00:04:12.630 --> 00:04:15.920
There are many, many artistic
continuities between the Capitol

00:04:15.920 --> 00:04:17.760
and the Thomas Jefferson
Building.

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:20.800
And many of the same
artists, particularly

00:04:20.800 --> 00:04:22.980
in the late 19th century,
early 20th century,

00:04:22.980 --> 00:04:25.560
that worked on the Jefferson
Building went on to work

00:04:25.560 --> 00:04:27.160
at the Capitol, or
worked at the Capitol,

00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:28.460
worked at the Jefferson
Building,

00:04:28.460 --> 00:04:29.760
and went back and forth.

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:32.920
So I will talk about
that as I go along, too.

00:04:32.920 --> 00:04:35.990
So those are the main
aims of my presentation.

00:04:35.990 --> 00:04:38.100
Let's start on in.

00:04:38.100 --> 00:04:42.890
Okay. Thomas Jefferson brings
neo-classical architecture

00:04:42.890 --> 00:04:45.490
to the United States.

00:04:45.490 --> 00:04:50.880
This is, again, as he did
this in the early 1800s,

00:04:50.880 --> 00:04:54.310
this is a tradition that, of
course, we live with today.

00:04:54.310 --> 00:04:56.050
He designed the very
first expression

00:04:56.050 --> 00:04:57.570
of neo-classical architecture,

00:04:57.570 --> 00:05:02.520
which is the Virginia
State Capitol right here.

00:05:02.520 --> 00:05:07.620
And indeed he ripped off
this design completely

00:05:07.620 --> 00:05:11.070
from the Maison Cafe,
which is in Nimes, France.

00:05:11.070 --> 00:05:15.060
So he just took the
Maison Cafe and lifted it,

00:05:15.060 --> 00:05:17.860
and put it in Richmond, Virginia
as the Virginia State Capitol.

00:05:17.860 --> 00:05:20.730
In a letter to Pierre
L'Enfant, 1791,

00:05:20.730 --> 00:05:22.530
Jefferson expressed a desire

00:05:22.530 --> 00:05:27.010
for a Capitol building designed
after, quote, "One of the models

00:05:27.010 --> 00:05:29.590
of antiquity which have
had the approbation

00:05:29.590 --> 00:05:31.430
of thousands of years."

00:05:31.430 --> 00:05:36.100
Jefferson believed that American
taste could improve by exposure

00:05:36.100 --> 00:05:39.190
to copies of classical
Roman architecture adapted

00:05:39.190 --> 00:05:40.780
to our new country.

00:05:40.780 --> 00:05:43.330
He also believed that the
Capitol could provide the

00:05:43.330 --> 00:05:46.960
premier example of architecture
in the United States.

00:05:46.960 --> 00:05:49.640
And he hoped this style would be
copied throughout the country.

00:05:49.640 --> 00:05:53.530
And, of course, as we all know,
it was to a certain extent.

00:05:53.530 --> 00:05:56.160
He put a huge amount of
care and attention to detail

00:05:56.160 --> 00:05:57.460
in the design of the Capitol.

00:05:57.460 --> 00:06:00.110
Some scholars say as much
as he did to Monticello.

00:06:00.110 --> 00:06:01.410
I'm not sure.

00:06:01.410 --> 00:06:02.710
But it's important
for you all to know

00:06:02.710 --> 00:06:05.610
that that he was
extremely detail oriented

00:06:05.610 --> 00:06:07.320
in making those decisions.

00:06:07.320 --> 00:06:11.390
In 1807, Benjamin Latrobe
writes to Thomas Jefferson,

00:06:11.390 --> 00:06:15.100
and I quote, "It is no
flattery to say that YOU,"

00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:18.390
and the caps are
Latrobe's, y, o, u, in caps,

00:06:18.390 --> 00:06:20.880
"have planted the
arts in your country.

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:24.810
The works already erected in
this city are the monuments

00:06:24.810 --> 00:06:29.390
of your judgment and of
your zeal and of your taste.

00:06:29.390 --> 00:06:31.910
The first," and again
the caps are Latrobe's,

00:06:31.910 --> 00:06:34.590
"sculpture that adorned an
American public building

00:06:34.590 --> 00:06:38.700
perpetuates your love and
protection of the arts."

00:06:38.700 --> 00:06:43.090
Okay? So Thomas Jefferson has a
role in our Jefferson Building

00:06:43.090 --> 00:06:44.600
that is quite apart
from the Library.

00:06:44.600 --> 00:06:47.150
What he is doing is
establishing a tradition

00:06:47.150 --> 00:06:50.010
which then is carried through
into our building today,

00:06:50.010 --> 00:06:53.130
and its design and construction.

00:06:53.130 --> 00:06:55.470
Okay. So let's start
at the beginning.

00:06:55.470 --> 00:06:58.380
William Thornton is the very
first architect of the Capitol.

00:06:58.380 --> 00:07:02.240
In 1797, much of the
central facade of Thornton,

00:07:02.240 --> 00:07:04.820
today central facade
particularly on the east side,

00:07:04.820 --> 00:07:08.010
is Thornton's other works
in our area, of course,

00:07:08.010 --> 00:07:10.420
and by Thornton our Octagon
House and Tudor Place

00:07:10.420 --> 00:07:12.390
and Woodlawn Plantation.

00:07:12.390 --> 00:07:15.240
By the way, he was born
in 1759 in Jost Van Dyke

00:07:15.240 --> 00:07:16.760
in the British Virgin Islands.

00:07:16.760 --> 00:07:20.980
He was a physician, an inventor,
a painter and an architect.

00:07:20.980 --> 00:07:25.730
And his design for the Capitol
was indeed accepted in 1793.

00:07:25.730 --> 00:07:32.140
He was inspired by the Louvre
and also by the Pantheon.

00:07:32.140 --> 00:07:35.680
And this is his original design.

00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:36.980
This dome, as you know,

00:07:36.980 --> 00:07:39.650
is definitely not the
dome we have today.

00:07:39.650 --> 00:07:44.160
But this facade is the facade
that really remains today.

00:07:44.160 --> 00:07:46.160
Can everybody see my cursor?

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:51.350
Okay. So the original
north wing of the Library.

00:07:51.350 --> 00:07:53.840
You may be familiar
with this print.

